This article discusses the author's journey from exploring HTMX to developing their own alternative called MESH (Modular Element SSR with Hydration). While appreciating HTMX's "HTML-first" approach to web development as a pushback against JavaScript frameworks, the author found HTMX lacked structure, likening it to "declarative jQuery" with potential for disorganized code. MESH was created as a solution, built on the principle of "one component = one endpoint," combining HTML-first development with the structured approach of SPA frameworks through Web Components and Declarative Shadow DOM.

## Key Insight
The single most valuable takeaway is the tension in modern web development between structure and simplicityâ€”while HTMX offers a return to HTML-first development that could reduce JavaScript dependence, it lacks the organizational benefits that make SPA frameworks appealing to developers.
